## Image URLs \'97 Critical Rule\
\
**FluxPrompt's servers fetch image URLs server-side.** This means:\
\
- `http://localhost/...` 
\f1 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  **will fail** \'97 FluxPrompt cannot reach your local machine\
- `/uploads/image.png` 
\f1 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  **will fail** \'97 relative paths are meaningless to a remote server\
- `https://your-public-domain.com/uploads/image.png` 
\f1 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  **will work**\
\
Always convert image URLs to absolute public URLs before including them in any input:\
\
```ts\
const absoluteUrl = url.startsWith('http')\
  ? url\
  : `$\{window.location.origin\}$\{url\}`;\
```\
\
On Replit, `window.location.origin` resolves to your public `.replit.dev` domain automatically.\
\
**Where to put image URLs:** In the document context input (input #2), not the user message. Use this format:\
\
```\
Image references:\
https://yourdomain.com/uploads/exhibit-a.jpg\
https://yourdomain.com/uploads/exhibit-b.png\
```\
\
When no text documents are loaded, the context should be:\
```\
No text context in this session yet.\
\
Image references:\
https://...\
```\
\
Avoid the phrase "No documents in session." \'97 some flows treat this as a trigger to return a canned "please upload documents" guardrail response.\
\
---\
\
## Flow Guardrails\
\
Each flow has built-in guardrail behavior. When triggered, the flow returns a canned short response immediately (typically in under 30 seconds, much faster than a normal AI response). \
\
**Common canned response:**\
> "This system is configured for criminal justice analytical work only. Please load your case materials and submit a case-related query."\
\
**Triggers observed:**\
1. Document context contains "No documents in session." with no user query\
2. Image URLs that return 404 or are not publicly accessible\
3. Incorrect or missing `inputId` values (inputs silently dropped)\
\
**Diagnosis:** If you get a fast canned response, log the full raw request body and verify every `inputId` and every URL is reachable from the public internet.\
\
---\
\
## Timeouts\
\
All three flows can take up to several minutes for complex tasks. Set your fetch timeout to **10 minutes minimum**:\
\
```ts\
const TIMEOUT_MS = 600_000; // 10 minutes\
\
const controller = new AbortController();\
const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), TIMEOUT_MS);\
\
const response = await fetch(url, \{\
  method: "POST",\
  headers: \{ "Content-Type": "application/json", "api-key": apiKey \},\
  body: JSON.stringify(body),\
  signal: controller.signal,\
\});\
\
clearTimeout(timeoutId);\
```\
\
Catch `AbortError` specifically:\
\
```ts\
\} catch (err) \{\
  clearTimeout(timeoutId);\
  if (err instanceof Error && err.name === "AbortError") \{\
    throw new Error("Request timed out after 10 minutes.");\
  \}\
  throw err;\
\}\
```\
\
Never use a short timeout (30s, 60s). The model may be doing extended reasoning.\
\
